### 4. Implementation Updates

#### Firefox Implementation Update
* **Presenter:** Max Weber
* **Slides:** [Update on Firefox implementation](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-happy-update-on-firefox-implementation-00)
* **Technical Details:**
  * Happy Eyeballs v3 is now enabled by default in Firefox Nightly (representing approximately 15,000 users). The core state machine has been modularized into a reusable, deterministic library (`mozilla/ipviballs`).
  * Current parameters: 25ms resolution delay (draft suggests 50ms); 50ms initial connection attempt delay with a 2x multiplier (draft suggests 250ms constant).
  * Telemetry shows the first connection attempt succeeds in 84% of cases. Only one attempt is made in 86% of sessions.
  * Firefox interleaves both IP families (IPv6/IPv4) and protocols (QUIC/TCP), attempting QUIC v6, QUIC v4, TCP v6, then TCP v4.
  * HTTPS record positive responses are observed in roughly 7% of connections.
  * **Discussion:** Lorenzo Colitti asked what proportion of second-attempt successes are due to actual first-attempt failures versus simply sending concurrent packets to the network. Gorry Fairhurst suggested evaluating battery impact, protocol flapping, and analyzing telemetry across cellular versus fixed networks. Tommy Pauly noted that Apple sees a significantly higher rate of positive HTTPS record responses (~17%).

#### Chromium Implementation Update
* **Presenter:** Kenichi Ishibashi
* **Slides:** [Update on Chromium implementation (revised)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-happy-update-on-chromium-implementation-revised-00)
* **Technical Details:**
  * Chromium is actively refactoring its connection management layer to share DNS resolutions between TCP and QUIC and avoid waiting for all DNS responses.
  * For TCP, incremental resolution is fully implemented and near shipping. It implements a 15ms resolution delay when a AAAA response is outstanding.
  * For QUIC, incremental resolution is in development. Chromium will start handshakes as soon as a usable endpoint is resolved, falling back to other family addresses if the first attempt is slow or fails.
  * Optimistic DNS groundwork has been completed in the resolver ("long-name" cache usage mode). Field trials for TCP are planned.
  * **Discussion:** Johannes Zirngibl asked whether QUIC is raced against TCP establishment or TLS-over-TCP. Nidhi Jaju clarified that Chromium waits for the TLS handshake to complete. Ben Schwartz asked about stale cache lifetime limits; Kenichi Ishibashi responded that the cache is cleared upon browser relaunch and network changes, though on desktops it could persist for weeks. Ben Schwartz noted that if TCP succeeds before QUIC, QUIC handshakes are allowed to continue in the background so future requests can upgrade to QUIC.

#### Apple Implementation Update
* **Presenter:** Tommy Pauly
* **Slides:** [Apple Implementation Update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-happy-apple-implementation-update-00)
* **Technical Details:**
  * Apple’s Happy Eyeballs v3 implementation relies on historical RTT data rather than static timers.
  * Telemetry indicates that the first attempt wins the race in 97% of connections.
  * Recent beta updates ensure that Happy Eyeballs reordering occurs strictly within SVCB priority groups to respect the operator's specified priorities.
  * Telemetry for the delta between A and AAAA resolution times shows a P90 of 17ms, a P95 of 34ms, and a P99 of 100ms.
  * **Discussion:** Andrew Alston asked for more telemetry focusing specifically on the "unhappy path" (failures) to understand when IPv6 fails and Happy Eyeballs successfully rescues the connection.

