### 7. Considerations for Happy Eyeballs Error Reporting
* **Presenter:** Philipp Tiesel
* **Slides:** [Considerations for Happy Eyeballs Error Reporting](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-happy-considerations-for-happy-eyeballs-error-reporting-00)
* **Technical Details:**
  * Discussed the use cases, target audiences, and privacy constraints of reporting Happy Eyeballs failures.
  * Defined five primary personas: Local developers, Corporate/managed network operators, Service providers (carriers), Intermediate transit providers, and Content providers/CDNs.
  * **Discussion:** Lars Eggert expressed strong privacy concerns regarding exposing connection and fallback telemetry directly to third-party service and transit providers, suggesting focus should remain on local debugging and corporate networks. Kazuho Oku questioned the necessity of building complex reporting pipelines if existing platform/browser profiling tools already capture this data. Philipp Tiesel and Jordi Palet emphasized that network operators need some level of reporting because Happy Eyeballs effectively hides severe IPv6 deployment failures (such as IPv6 routing black holes) from immediate detection. Brian Trammell suggested reviving a "happy-sad" reporting draft to explore what metadata could safely be exposed to help network debugging.

